    en: "A wage assignment is a written agreement where a worker authorizes their employer to send part of their pay directly to a creditor. New York General Obligations Law § 5-1801 strictly limits voluntary wage assignments. They generally cannot exceed 10 percent of wages and require the worker's written consent for each pay period. Voluntary wage assignments are different from involuntary income executions (the standard wage garnishment under CPLR 5231) and from court-ordered child support deductions. Many predatory lenders try to use wage assignments to bypass the standard garnishment process, but most of these attempts violate NY law."
