  whatItMeans: {
    en: "A wage assignment is an agreement where a worker assigns part of their future earnings directly to a creditor. The creditor sends the assignment to the worker's employer, and the employer takes the agreed-upon amount out of each paycheck and sends it to the creditor. Unlike a wage garnishment, a wage assignment does not require a court order — it relies on the worker's prior written consent.\n\nThe NY law sharply limits wage assignments. Throughout the 20th century, payday lenders, used-furniture dealers, and other consumer creditors used wage assignments aggressively. A consumer would sign a small loan with a wage assignment buried in the fine print, fall behind, and find their entire paycheck garnished without ever going to court. NY General Obligations Law § 5-1801 was enacted to stop this and stays among the strongest worker-protection statutes in the country.\n\nThe 10 percent cap. NY General Obligations Law § 5-1801 limits voluntary wage assignments to no more than 10 percent of the worker's wages. A wage assignment for more than 10 percent is unenforceable. The 10 percent cap exists alongside the standard CPLR 5231 income execution cap (which limits involuntary garnishment to 10 percent of weekly disposable earnings or the amount by which weekly earnings exceed 30 times the federal minimum wage, whichever is less).\n\nWritten consent for each pay period. NY law requires that the worker's consent to a wage assignment be specific to the pay period in which the deduction is made. A blanket pre-authorization signed once at the time of the loan is not enforceable for future pay periods unless the worker re-confirms. This is one of the strictest forms of consent in any U.S. state. The practical effect: a creditor cannot rely on a one-time signature to keep deducting from a worker's pay indefinitely.\n\nUnion dues and benefits — different rules. Union dues, union initiation fees, and benefit-fund contributions deducted from pay under a collective bargaining agreement are governed by NY Labor Law § 193 and federal labor law, not by General Obligations Law § 5-1801. These deductions are generally enforceable as long as the worker is represented by the union and has authorized the deductions in writing.\n\nChild support and spousal support — court-ordered, not voluntary. A court-ordered income withholding for child support or spousal support under NY Family Court Act § 461 or NY Domestic Relations Law § 244 is not a voluntary wage assignment. It is mandatory and proceeds without the worker's consent. The withholding amount can be up to 50 percent of disposable earnings (60 percent if the worker has no other dependents). These deductions are processed through the NY Child Support Processing Center.\n\nFederal student loan administrative wage garnishment — different rules. The U.S. Department of Education can garnish up to 15 percent of disposable pay for defaulted federal student loans without a court order under 20 USC § 1095a. This is administrative wage garnishment and is governed by federal regulations, not NY General Obligations Law § 5-1801. The worker has the right to a pre-garnishment hearing and can negotiate a payment plan to avoid garnishment.\n\nWhen a creditor sends a wage assignment to an employer. The employer should verify several things before taking deductions. Is the assignment from a creditor with a written, specific consent signed by the worker that is current for this pay period? Is the deduction within the 10 percent cap? Has the employer notified the worker that the assignment was received and is about to be honored?\n\nThe employer is at risk if the assignment turns out to be defective. An employer who deducts from wages on the basis of a defective wage assignment faces a separate claim by the worker for the wages improperly withheld plus liquidated damages under NY Labor Law § 193. Most employers refer wage assignments to legal counsel before deducting.\n\nWhen the worker objects. A worker who learns of a pending wage assignment can revoke their consent in writing at any time before the deduction. The revocation should be sent to both the creditor and the employer, by certified mail with return receipt. Once revoked, no further deductions can be made unless the creditor obtains a court judgment and a separate income execution under CPLR 5231.\n\nFor workers facing wage assignment as part of a debt collection. The standard advice: do not sign any document containing a wage assignment without legal review. The creditor often has other options to pursue the debt (small claims court, regular collection action) that do not require giving up a portion of pay before any court proceeding. A debt that goes through small claims allows the worker to raise defenses, negotiate, and challenge the amount owed before any deduction.\n\nFor borrowers in default on payday loans. Payday lenders historically used wage assignments to collect quickly. NY does not allow most payday lending — NY Banking Law 14-a sets a 16 percent civil usury cap on most consumer loans, and Penal Law 190.40 makes interest above 25 percent per annum criminal usury, far below the typical payday loan rate of 300 percent or more. Many out-of-state and online payday lenders operate in NY illegally, and their wage assignments are unenforceable. The Department of Financial Services at [number being verified] receives complaints about illegal payday lending in NY.\n\nFor an employer that receives an unfamiliar assignment. The employer can decline to honor an assignment that does not meet NY General Obligations Law § 5-1801 requirements. The employer's decline letter to the creditor should cite the specific deficiency (no current consent, exceeds 10 percent cap, lack of NY consumer credit license). The worker is informed of the decline as well.\n\nDistinction from CPLR 5231 income execution. NY's standard wage garnishment is the Income Execution under CPLR § 5231. It requires a money judgment in court, then service of the income execution on the worker, then service on the employer. The 10 percent cap and exemption rules apply. An income execution is involuntary — the worker did not consent to it. The income execution and the voluntary wage assignment are different legal mechanisms with different rules. Most wage deductions in NY are income executions, not voluntary wage assignments."
  },

